mons category|Music in 1943}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1943 In Music}}\n[[Category:1943 in music| ]]\n[[Category:20th century in music]]\n[[Category:Music by year]]\n", "name_user": "KR7907", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1943_in_music"}
{"title_page": "Virgin Orbit", "text_new": "{{Short description|A private launcher services provider}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Virgin Orbit\n| logo = Virgin Orbin company logo 2017.png\n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| logo_padding = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| trading_name = \n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| traded_as = \n| ISIN = \n| industry = [[aerospace engineering|Aerospace]]\n| predecessor = [[Virgin Galactic]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2017|03|02}}\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| hq_location = \n| hq_location_city = [[Long Beach, California]]\n| hq_location_country = United States\n| num_locations = \n| num_locations_year = <!-- Year of num_locations data (if known) -->\n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = Dan Hart <ref>{{cite news |last=Fernholz |first=Tim |date=June 13, 2017 |title=Virgin Orbit\u2019s newly-minted CEO will use psychology to launch satellites faster than anyone else |url=https://qz.com/1003876/virgin-orbits-newly-minted-ceo-will-use-psychology-to-launch-satellites-faster-than-anyone-else/ | work=Quartz |access-date=2017-06-13 }}</ref> ([[President (corporate title)|President]] and [[CEO]])\n| products = [[LauncherOne]]\n| brands = \n| production = \n| production_year = <!-- Year of production data (if known) -->\n| services = [[Orbital spaceflight|Orbital]] [[rocket launch]]\n| revenue = \n| revenue_year = <!-- Year of revenue data (if known) -->\n| operating_income = \n| income_year = <!-- Year of operating_income data (if known) -->\n| net_income = <!-- or: | profit = -->\n| net_income_year = <!-- or: | profit_year = --><!-- Year of net_income/profit data (if known) -->\n| assets = \n| assets_year = <!-- Year of assets data (if known) -->\n| equity = \n| equity_year = <!-- Year of equity data (if known) -->\n| owners = {{Unbulleted list|[[Aabar Investments PJS]]|[[Virgin Group]]}}\n| num_employees = 390\n| num_employees_year = 2017\n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| module = <!-- Used to embed other templates -->\n| website = {{URL|virginorbit.com}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Virgin Orbit''' is a company within the [[Virgin Group]] which plans to [[launch service provider|provide launch services]] for [[small satellite]]s. The company was formed in 2017 to develop the air-launched [[LauncherOne]] rocket, launched from [[Cosmic Girl (aircraft)|Cosmic Girl]], which had previously been a project of [[Virgin Galactic]].<ref name=Space-2017-03-02>{{cite news |url= http://www.space.com/35892-virgin-galactic-unveils-virgin-orbit-small-satellites.html |title= Virgin Galactic Unveils Spin-Off Virgin Orbit for Small-Satellite Launches |author= Irene Klotz |date= 2 March 2017 |publisher= [[Space.com]] }}</ref> Based in [[Long Beach, California]], Virgin Orbit has more than 300 employees led by president Dan Hart, a former vice president of government satellite systems at [[Boeing]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davenport |first=Christian |date=March 2, 2017 |title=Richard Branson starting a new venture dedicated to launching small satellites into space |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2017/03/02/richard-branson-starting-a-new-venture-dedicated-to-launching-small-satellites-into-space/ | work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=2017-03-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 2, 2017 |title=Virgin Galactic Makes Satellite Launch Service New Company  |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/california/articles/2017-03-02/virgin-galactic-makes-satellite-launch-service-new-company | work=[[U.S. News & World Report]] |access-date=2017-03-08 }}</ref>\n\nVirgin Orbit focuses on small [[satellite]] launch, which is one of three capabilities being focused on by [[Virgin Galactic]]. These capabilities are: [[human spaceflight]] operations, small satellite launch, and advanced aerospace design, manufacturing, and test.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome, Virgin Orbit!|url=http://www.virgingalactic.com/welcome-virgin-orbit/|website=Virgin Galactic|publisher=Virgin Galactic|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308222740/http://www.virgingalactic.com/welcome-virgin-orbit/|archivedate=8 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Vehicles==\n===LauncherOne===\n{{main|LauncherOne}}\n\n===Cosmic Girl===\n{{main|Cosmic Girl (aircraft)}}<ref>{{Cite book|title=Empire State|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Other projects==\n===Ventilators===\nIn response to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] in early 2020, Virgin Orbit announced it was a partner in a new venture to build comparatively low-grade [[mechanical ventilator]]s (breathing machines) -- specifically \"[[bridge ventilator]]s\" for partially recovered patients and patients not in intensive care -- to address the critical global shortage of mechanical ventilators during the pandemic. To develop and produce them, Virgin Global --  with the [[University of California Irvine]] and the [[University of Texas at Austin]] -- formed the [[Bridge Ventilator Consortium]]. They had a prototype awaiting approval by the US [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA), in March, and hoped to begin production in April.<ref name=\"virgin_orbit_designs_2020_03_space_com\">[https://www.space.com/virgin-orbit-designs-ventilator-to-fight-coronavirus.html \"Virgin Orbit designs new ventilator as part of Virgin Group's efforts to combat coronavirus,\"] March, 2020, '''[[Space.com]],''' retrieved April 2, 2020</ref><ref name=\"companies_helping_2020_03_businessinsider_com\">[https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-companies-helping-meet-shortages-of-ventilators-gowns-masks-hand-sanitizer-healthcare \"Coronavirus: Companies are helping meet shortages of ventilators, gowns, and more,\"] March, 2020, ''[[Business Insider]],'' retrieved April 2, 2020.</ref><ref name=\"bransons_virgin_2020_03_30_nbc_news\">[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/30/bransons-virgin-orbit-to-begin-coronavirus-ventilator-mass-production.html \"Branson's Virgin Orbit to begin coronavirus ventilator mass production,\"] March 30, 2020, ''[[NBC News]],'' retrieved April 2, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\nIn October 2019, Virgin Orbit announced that Matthew Stannard was joining as a pilot on a three-year contract. Stannard had previously served in the [[Royal Air Force]] as a test and evaluation pilot notably on [[Eurofighter_Typhoon|Typhoon]] jets. Orbit is about to start testing of its [[Cosmic Girl (aircraft)|''Cosmic Girl'']] launch platform.<ref name=\"2019-10-04_SD\">[http://www.spacedaily.com/reports/Virgin_Orbit_selects_RAF_pilot_as_it_plans_satellite_launch_program_999.html Virgin Orbit selects RAF pilot as it plans satellite launch program], Ed Adamczyk, [[SpaceDaily]], 2019-10-04</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commonscat inline}}\n\n{{Virgin Group}}\n{{Virgin Galactic}}\n\n[[Category:Virgin Group]]\n[[Category:Aerospace companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Private spaceflight companies]]\n[[Category:Commercial launch service providers]]\n[[Category:Virgin Galactic]]\n[[Category:Technology companies based in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Long Beach, California]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 2017]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2017]]\n[[Category:2017 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Aabar Investments]]\n[[Category:Virgin Orbit| ]]\n\n\n{{US-company-stub}}\n{{tech-company-stub}}\n{{rocket-stub}}\n{{space-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|A private launcher services provider}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Virgin Orbit\n| logo = Virgin Orbin company logo 2017.png\n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| logo_padding = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| trading_name = \n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| traded_as = \n| ISIN = \n| industry = [[aerospace engineering|Aerospace]]\n| predecessor = [[Virgin Galactic]]\n| founded = {{Start date and age|2017|03|02}}\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| hq_location = \n| hq_location_city = [[Long Beach, California]]\n| hq_location_country = United States\n| num_locations = \n| num_locations_year = <!-- Year of num_locations data (if known) -->\n| area_served = <!-- or: | areas_served = -->\n| key_people = Dan Hart <ref>{{cite news |last=Fernholz |first=Tim |date=June 13, 2017 |title=Virgin Orbit\u2019s newly-minted CEO will use psychology to launch satellites faster than anyone else |url=https://qz.com/1003876/virgin-orbits-newly-minted-ceo-will-use-psychology-to-launch-satellites-faster-than-anyone-else/ | work=Quartz |access-date=2017-06-13 }}</ref> ([[President (corporate title)|President]] and [[CEO]])\n| products = [[LauncherOne]]\n| brands = \n| production = \n| production_year = <!-- Year of production data (if known) -->\n| services = [[Orbital spaceflight|Orbital]] [[rocket launch]]\n| revenue = \n| revenue_year = <!-- Year of revenue data (if known) -->\n| operating_income = \n| income_year = <!-- Year of operating_income data (if known) -->\n| net_income = <!-- or: | profit = -->\n| net_income_year = <!-- or: | profit_year = --><!-- Year of net_income/profit data (if known) -->\n| assets = \n| assets_year = <!-- Year of assets data (if known) -->\n| equity = \n| equity_year = <!-- Year of equity data (if known) -->\n| owners = {{Unbulleted list|[[Aabar Investments PJS]]|[[Virgin Group]]}}\n| num_employees = 390\n| num_employees_year = 2017\n| parent = \n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| module = <!-- Used to embed other templates -->\n| website = {{URL|virginorbit.com}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Virgin Orbit''' is a company within the [[Virgin Group]] which plans to [[launch service provider|provide launch services]] for [[small satellite]]s. The company was formed in 2017 to develop the air-launched [[LauncherOne]] rocket, launched from [[Cosmic Girl (aircraft)|Cosmic Girl]], which had previously been a project of [[Virgin Galactic]].<ref name=Space-2017-03-02>{{cite news |url= http://www.space.com/35892-virgin-galactic-unveils-virgin-orbit-small-satellites.html |title= Virgin Galactic Unveils Spin-Off Virgin Orbit for Small-Satellite Launches |author= Irene Klotz |date= 2 March 2017 |publisher= [[Space.com]] }}</ref> Based in [[Long Beach, California]], Virgin Orbit has more than 300 employees led by president Dan Hart, a former vice president of government satellite systems at [[Boeing]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Davenport |first=Christian |date=March 2, 2017 |title=Richard Branson starting a new venture dedicated to launching small satellites into space |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2017/03/02/richard-branson-starting-a-new-venture-dedicated-to-launching-small-satellites-into-space/ | work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=2017-03-08 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 2, 2017 |title=Virgin Galactic Makes Satellite Launch Service New Company  |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/california/articles/2017-03-02/virgin-galactic-makes-satellite-launch-service-new-company | work=[[U.S. News & World Report]] |access-date=2017-03-08 }}</ref>\n\nVirgin Orbit focuses on small [[satellite]] launch, which is one of three capabilities being focused on by [[Virgin Galactic]]. These capabilities are: [[human spaceflight]] operations, small satellite launch, and advanced aerospace design, manufacturing, and test.<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome, Virgin Orbit!|url=http://www.virgingalactic.com/welcome-virgin-orbit/|website=Virgin Galactic|publisher=Virgin Galactic|accessdate=9 March 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170308222740/http://www.virgingalactic.com/welcome-virgin-orbit/|archivedate=8 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Vehicles==\n===LauncherOne===\n{{main|LauncherOne}}\n\n===Cosmic Girl===\n{{main|Cosmic Girl (aircraft)}}<ref>{{Cite book|title=Empire State|last=|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n==Other projects==\n===Ventilators===\nIn response to the [[COVID-19 pandemic]] in early 2020, Virgin Orbit announced it was a partner in a new venture to build comparatively low-grade [[mechanical ventilator]]s (breathing machines) -- specifically \"[[bridge ventilator]]s\" for partially recovered patients and patients not in intensive care -- to address the critical global shortage of mechanical ventilators during the pandemic. To develop and produce them, Virgin Global --  with the [[University of California Irvine]] and the [[University of Texas at Austin]] -- formed the [[Bridge Ventilator Consortium]]. They had a prototype awaiting approval by the US [[Food and Drug Administration]] (FDA), in March, and hoped to begin production in April.<ref name=\"virgin_orbit_designs_2020_03_space_com\">[https://www.space.com/virgin-orbit-designs-ventilator-to-fight-coronavirus.html \"Virgin Orbit designs new ventilator as part of Virgin Group's efforts to combat coronavirus,\"] March, 2020, '''[[Space.com]],''' retrieved April 2, 2020</ref><ref name=\"companies_helping_2020_03_businessinsider_com\">[https://www.businessinsider.com/coronavirus-companies-helping-meet-shortages-of-ventilators-gowns-masks-hand-sanitizer-healthcare \"Coronavirus: Companies are helping meet shortages of ventilators, gowns, and more,\"] March, 2020, ''[[Business Insider]],'' retrieved April 2, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\nIn October 2019, Virgin Orbit announced that Matthew Stannard was joining as a pilot on a three-year contract. Stannard had previously served in the [[Royal Air Force]] as a test and evaluation pilot notably on [[Eurofighter_Typhoon|Typhoon]] jets. Orbit is about to start testing of its [[Cosmic Girl (aircraft)|''Cosmic Girl'']] launch platform.<ref name=\"2019-10-04_SD\">[http://www.spacedaily.com/reports/Virgin_Orbit_selects_RAF_pilot_as_it_plans_satellite_launch_program_999.html Virgin Orbit selects RAF pilot as it plans satellite launch program], Ed Adamczyk, [[SpaceDaily]], 2019-10-04</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commonscat inline}}\n\n{{Virgin Group}}\n{{Virgin Galactic}}\n\n[[Category:Virgin Group]]\n[[Category:Aerospace companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Private spaceflight companies]]\n[[Category:Commercial launch service providers]]\n[[Category:Virgin Galactic]]\n[[Category:Technology companies based in Greater Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Long Beach, California]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 2017]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2017]]\n[[Category:2017 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Aabar Investments]]\n[[Category:Virgin Orbit| ]]\n\n\n{{US-company-stub}}\n{{tech-company-stub}}\n{{rocket-stub}}\n{{space-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Zxtxtxz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eVentilators:add ref cite", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virgin_Orbit"}
{"title_page": "Stuck on You (Elvis Presley song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Stuck on You\n| cover      = Stuck_on_you_Elvis_single.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption = UK single cover art\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Elvis Presley]]\n| album      =\n| B-side     = [[Fame and Fortune (Elvis Presley song)|Fame and Fortune]]\n| released   = March 23, 1960\n| format     = [[Single (music)|Vinyl single]]\n| recorded   = March 21, 1960, RCA Studios, [[Nashville, Tennessee]]\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Rock and roll]], [[Pop music|pop]], [[rhythm and blues]]\n| length     = 2:18\n| label      = [[RCA Victor]]\n| writer     = [[Aaron Schroeder]]<br />[[John Leslie McFarland|J. Leslie McFarland]]\n| producer   =\n| prev_title = [[A Big Hunk o' Love]]\n| prev_year  = 1959\n| title      =\n| title2     = [[Fame and Fortune (Elvis Presley song)|Fame and Fortune]]\n| next_title = [[It's Now or Never (song)|It's Now or Never]]\n| next_year  = 1960\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|jVqR2PwX428|\"Stuck on You\" (audio)}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Stuck on You'''\" was [[Elvis Presley]]'s first hit single after his two-year stint in the US Army, reaching number one in 1960 in the US. \n\nHe recorded the song during March 1960, and the single was released within weeks and went to number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart in late-April 1960, becoming his first number-one single of the 1960s and thirteenth overall. \"Stuck on You\" peaked at number six on the R&B chart.<ref>{{Cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=468}}</ref> The song knocked Percy Faith's \"[[Theme from A Summer Place]]\" from the top spot, ending its nine-week run at number one on the chart. The record reached number three in the UK. \n\nThe song was written by [[Aaron Schroeder]] and [[J. Leslie McFarland]] and published by Gladys Music, Elvis Presley's publishing company.\n\nThe single had a special picture sleeve with the RCA Victor logo and catalog number on the top right corner and included, in large letters, \"ELVIS\" in red on the top right. On the bottom left appeared the statement: \"Elvis' 1st new recording for his 50,000,000 fans all over the world.\" The U.S. picture sleeve had photos of Elvis on the left top corner and the lower right corner. The New Zealand sleeve did not have the photographs on the corners but had the \"45 R.P.M.\" designation on the top right corner.<ref>[https://www.discogs.com/Elvis-Presley-With-The-Jordanaires-Stuck-On-You-Fame-And-Fortune/release/2134129 Stuck On You/Fame and Fortune. Discongs.]</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n'''The Blue Moon Boys'''\n*[[Elvis Presley]] - lead vocals, acoustic rhythm guitar\n*[[Scotty Moore]] - lead guitar\n* [[D. J. Fontana]] - drums\n'''Additional personnel and production staff'''\n* [[Hank Garland]] - bass guitar\n* [[Bob Moore]] - double bass\n* [[Floyd Cramer]] - piano\n* [[Buddy Harman]] - drums\n* [[The Jordanaires]] - backing vocals\n\n==Chart performance==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart (1960)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|Australia \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Belgium \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|Canada ([[CHUM Chart|CHUM]] ''Hit Parade'')<ref>{{cite web|url=|title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date=19XX-XX-XX |accessdate=2020-03-02}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Denmark \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|-\n|Germany \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|23\n|-\n|{{singlechart|Ireland2|10|song=Stuck on You|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}\n|-\n|Netherlands \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Norway \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|2\n|-\n|Sweden \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|UK \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' 